Iterative Inorder Traversal

Inorder traversal follows:

Left → Root → Right

In iterative inorder traversal, we use a stack to simulate the recursive function call stack.

Unlike preorder traversal, we do not process the node immediately.
First, we keep moving toward the left subtree.

Iterative Approach
Create an empty result list to store traversal output.
Create an empty stack using LinkedList<TreeNode>.
Create a pointer called current and initialize it with the root node.
Repeat the traversal while:
current node is not null
OR
stack is not empty
Move as far left as possible:
Push the current node into the stack.
Move to the left child.
Continue until current becomes null.
Once there is no more left subtree:
Pop the top node from the stack.
Process the node by adding its value to the result list.

After processing the node:

Move to its right subtree using:
current = current.right;
Repeat the same process until both:
current becomes null
stack becomes empty
Return the final result list.
Iterative Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {

    public List<Integer> inorderTraversal(TreeNode root) {

        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

        inorderHelper(root, result);

        return result;
    }

    private void inorderHelper(TreeNode root, List<Integer> result) {

        LinkedList<TreeNode> stack = new LinkedList<>();

        TreeNode current = root;

        while (current != null || !stack.isEmpty()) {

            while (current != null) {

                stack.push(current);

                current = current.left;
            }

            current = stack.pop();

            result.add(current.val);

            current = current.right;
        }
    }
}



General Iteration Steps

Always remember:

GO LEFT
PUSH NODE
GO LEFT

LEFT FINISHED?

POP NODE
PROCESS NODE
MOVE RIGHT
Important Intuition

Inorder traversal wants:

Left subtree first

So iterative inorder always keeps moving left before processing any node.

Only after the entire left subtree is completed do we process the root node.

Then traversal continues toward the right subtree.

Core Difference from Preorder
Traversal	Processing Time
Preorder	Process immediately
Inorder	Process after left subtree



