RECURSIVE APPROACH :

Recursive Relation of Inorder Traversal

Inorder traversal follows:

Left → Root → Right

This means:

First traverse the entire left subtree.
Then process the current root node.
Then traverse the entire right subtree.
Recursive Inorder Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {

    public List<Integer> inorderTraversal(TreeNode root) {

        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

        inorderHelper(root, result);

        return result;
    }

    private void inorderHelper(TreeNode root, List<Integer> result) {

        if (root == null) {
            return;
        }

        inorderHelper(root.left, result);

        result.add(root.val);

        inorderHelper(root.right, result);
    }
}
What Recursion is Internally Doing

When recursion runs:

inorderHelper(root.left, result);

Java does NOT immediately forget the current node.

Instead:

The current function call gets stored in memory
inside the system call stack.

This allows Java to:

Pause current node processing
Go deeper into left subtree
Return back later
Continue remaining work
IMPORTANT CONCEPT

Recursion internally uses:

Function Call Stack

The iterative approach manually creates this same behavior using:

LinkedList<TreeNode> stack
Recursive Flow in Detail

Suppose recursive code reaches this node:

      4
     / \
    2   6

and execution starts here:

inorderHelper(4, result);
STEP 1 — Traverse Left
inorderHelper(4.left, result);

Meaning:

Pause node 4
Go to node 2

Now recursion again says:

inorderHelper(2.left, result);

Again:

Pause node 2
Go further left

This continues until:

left becomes null
STEP 2 — Base Case Reached

Eventually recursion reaches:

if(root == null)
{
    return;
}

Meaning:

No more left subtree exists.
Start returning back.
STEP 3 — Process Node

After returning from left subtree:

result.add(root.val);

Now current node gets processed.

This satisfies:

Left → Root
STEP 4 — Traverse Right

After processing current node:

inorderHelper(root.right, result);

Now recursion explores the right subtree.

This completes:

Left → Root → Right
HOW ITERATIVE VERSION SIMULATES THIS

Recursive code automatically stores paused nodes in:

System Call Stack

Iterative inorder manually stores them using:

stack.push(current);
RECURSIVE vs ITERATIVE MAPPING
Recursive Behavior	Iterative Equivalent
Function call pauses current node	Push node into stack
Go to left subtree	current = current.left
Return from recursion	stack.pop()
Process root	result.add(current.val)
Go to right subtree	current = current.right
